ivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Rhirid ap Edelfrych was born about 1060, in Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Edelfrych ap Peredur. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT    1060–":"umbes 1060–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1095–Male":"1095–Surnud","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","ABT    1060":"umbes 1060","1030":"1030","1095":"1095","1060":"1060","of,,Ceredigion,Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT    1060–":"noin 1060–Kuollut","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","1095–Male":"1095–Kuollut","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","ABT    1060":"noin 1060","1030":"1030","1095":"1095","1060":"1060","of,,Ceredigion,Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT    1060–":"environ 1060–Décédé","1060–Male":"1060–Décédé","1095–Male":"1095–Décédé","1030–Male":"1030–Décédé","ABT    1060":"environ 1060","1030":"1030","1095":"1095","1060":"1060","of